column4: Cyberbullying is a real fact. I don't know that someone could just rise above it.
column6: Feel sad for the vampire. But everything is okay towards the end.
column8: Not much variation in style or much going on in the story.
column10: Felt a little sad for the vampire knowing this is something people can experience in the real world.
column12: Not much to the characters in general, follow trope of bullies and the bullied person just being okay afterwards.
column14: The writing style is very consistent throughout--too consistent almost. Marcus is also not a name that strikes fear, so I wouldn't use it for a Vampire.
column19: We don't know the characters that well as they aren't really given background, so there's not much connection.
column21: The storyline is very typical and there's not a lot of variation in the sentences.
column23: I didn't really feel moved by this piece as there's not any conflict or storyline to connect to.
column25: One character is revealed to do something out of the norm of their usual behavior, but that's pretty much it.
column27: The names are very basic. The story is not fleshed out. There's little to no writing style.
column30: I do think political corruption and power-hungriness is a true thing we experience in this day and age.
column32: I feel a little empathetic towards Mcconell as he continues to put on a brave face despite his hardships.
column34: I wasn't too engaged. I think the introduction of Cecil Grant was interesting, though.
column36: I wasn't really emotional while reading this.
column38: There's different perspectives added into the story. But, the characters do follow the tropes of the "good" and "bad" politicians.
column40: The story has kind of a robotic feel to it, but some parts are different like the grammatical mistake with the dash towards the beginning of the paper (it has a space). Also, characters are introduced by their first and last name again.
column43: I do think that humans would want to retaliate these aliens, but I'm not sure they wouldn't at least consider the 4 hour work day before doing so.
column45: I don't really feel connected to any of these characters.
column47: I think the storyline is pretty basic, especially down to the names and plotline.
column49: I didn't really connect with this piece.
column51: These characters are all pretty one-dimensional as they all have one goal and don't stray from that, which I don't know how accurate that is.
column53: There are a lot of cliche phrases like "tornado" of thoughts and comparing "rich and poor," etc.
column56: I think this could happen, a sister could be grieving the death of a sibling. But, I also don't know why they would feel the need to lie about being twins.
column58: I feel empathy for the person being lied to as well as the character who's sister was murdered.
column60: I didn't find it engaging. I think the storyline was pretty basic and it followed the prompt almost exactly.
column62: I can understand feeling upset if this is something the reader has experienced in their own life, but personally, I did not really connect to this story.
column64: There's a twist about them being twins, but that is asked of in the prompt, so I don't think the characters are very complex.
column66: The first sentence basically repeats what the prompt is asking. There's also the same "lesson to be learned" at the end of the piece.
column69: I think that people are put into situations where they have to choose one person or the other often.
column71: I felt a little empathetic in the fact that Sarah had to choose between two relationships she wanted to keep
column73: There were some differences in stylistic elements, but that was kind of it.
column75: I don't really feel moved by the story.

column82: I'm not sure that Sarah would have just realized, as an adult, that she and her sister were twins.
column84: I didn't feel connected to the character.
column86: I didn't really feel engaged as this storyline was cliche.

column92: I immediately felt this was AI-generated when I read the last few sentences. It does not answer the prompt as this is supposed to be from the spouse's point of view.
column95: I feel the father is too accepting of this situation for the severity it entails.
column97: I didn't really feel connected to the characters as there wasn't much depth to them.
column99: The storyline and dialogue was sort of basic.
column101: I didn't really feel moved by this piece.
column103: The character follow tropes, and the conflict is resolved too easily.
column105: Again, this is from the point of view of the daughter, not the father, so it doesn't answer the prompt. Also, the age of the daughter is repeated twice.
column108: I do think there's truth in being afraid that you won't like what the person you love creates and how you might express that to them. But, I think their mind is changed too easily at the end without even talking to their partner.
column110: I feel for the character who has to come to terms with the fact that they do not love something that the person they love has created.
column112: There wasn't really anything I was engaged in. The writing style was very stagnant, and what the prompt was asking was answered too clearly.
column114: I wasn't really connected to this story.
column116: The character learns in the end that people are complex.

column121: I think that if someone were truly in an apocalypse, this may be a strategy they would try. But I also think that they would try to go out and find other people instead of solely using the telephone.
column123: I am a little empathetic for the character seems so lonely.
column125: I wasn't engaged as there wasn't any character or plot point to connect to.
column127: I didn't really feel connected to this piece.

column131: This is not exactly a short story, more like a summary that you would read inside the cover of a book.
column134: I think we would work together to rebel against the robots. But I don't know if we would have such a positive attitude about it.
column136: I don't really feel connected enough to the characters. Maybe Lila since she has faced adversity.
column138: I think the characters introduction was okay.
column140: I didn't really feel connected to the story.

column147: I think that a human would be convinced or tempted by an angel who promised them peace and serenity.
column149: There's not much to feel empathetic for here I feel, but maybe that I would also be scared and trusting of someone in a new setting.

column153: I felt a little conflicted because if I were in this position, I would probably feel more scared, but also confused like this character is.
column155: I think the main character is a little basic, but the switch from an evil angel and a pure demon is complex.
column157: I think the descriptions at the beginning of the piece indicate this to be human writing.
column160: I don't think depression can be cured that easy, and I wouldn't describe it as "darkness," nor do I think any other person really would.
column162: I feel that this is something many people struggle with. But, the way this story portrays it just kind of brushes depression off.
column164: I wasn't really engaged in the story as it didn't feel authentic.
column166: I do feel a little sad for the person experiencing this. But, I also feel a little mad as I don't think their depression can just be cured by having to help their dog.
column168: The only complexity is the role reversal, but this is introduced to us in the prompt. The conflict is resolved too easily.
column170: There's the "lesson to be learned" element I've found in AI writing. I also think a human would go with a more darkened storyline rather than just summing it up with a positive ending.
column173: I think the emotions are portrayed in a very human-like way with reactions matching how I would expect them to.
column175: I feel empathetic for Rachel who lost everything pretty much.
column177: I feel the storyline was a little basic, but I liked the writing style.

column183: I think the first part is very human-like. The descriptions are good. But, again, there's that "lesson to be learned" element. Also, the characters are very tropey from what you would expect in this prompt.

column190: There's not much action happening. It sort of just answers the prompt.
column192: I feel sad for the partner who is being lied to.
column194: The twist is expected, and the characters are tropey in contect of the piece.

column4: The story authentically captures the struggles and emotional journey of a centuries-old vampire finding solace and purpose in the world of video games.
